<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-05-27T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-05-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="151" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d151">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 Pacific War/221</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Secretary of
                                State</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-05-27">May 27, 1941</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The British Ambassador called at his request. He read a despatch from
                            Anthony Eden, Foreign Minister, in which he offered profuse apologies
                            for the tone and nature of a recent <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi>
                            regarding some phases of the Pacific area which the British Ambassador,
                            on his last visit to my office,<note n="7" xml:id="d151fn7">May 24; see
                                footnote 84, <ref target="#pg_212">p. 212</ref>.</note> proposed
                            that I should receive and file, but which he retained after some rather
                            vigorous comment on my part. The truth is that the Foreign Minister had
                            all of his facts wrong.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>C[<hi rend="smallcaps">ordell</hi>] H[<hi rend="smallcaps">ull</hi>]</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>